for Leaving Time?

00:00:57.990 --> 00:00:59.358
<i> Jodi Picoult: Well, it was...
 it had nothing to do</i>

00:00:59.358 --> 00:01:01.694
with elephants at
first actually. ( laughter )

00:01:01.694 --> 00:01:03.329 line:0%
So, I have three kids,

00:01:03.329 --> 00:01:06.266 line:0%
and my youngest is a daughter
named Sammy.

00:01:06.266 --> 00:01:09.135 line:0%
And she was getting ready
to go off to college.

00:01:09.135 --> 00:01:11.004
And her brothers had
already left,

00:01:11.004 --> 00:01:13.639
so, I was becoming
an empty nester.

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:16.842
And it upset me more than
I thought it was going to.

00:01:16.842 --> 00:01:18.544
I was really thinking about

00:01:18.544 --> 00:01:20.947
what it would be like
to be left behind.

00:01:20.947 --> 00:01:23.215
And somewhere in the middle
of all that thought,

00:01:23.215 --> 00:01:24.817
I read an article, probably

00:01:24.817 --> 00:01:26.552
in the National Geographic
magazine,

00:01:26.552 --> 00:01:29.722
that said that in the elephant
kingdom in the wild,

00:01:29.722 --> 00:01:31.457
a mother and
daughter elephant,

00:01:31.457 --> 00:01:33.326
stay together
their whole lives,

00:01:33.326 --> 00:01:34.794
until one of them dies.

00:01:34.794 --> 00:01:36.862
And I read that fact
and I thought,

00:01:36.862 --> 00:01:38.197
'well why don't we do
it that way?'

00:01:38.197 --> 00:01:40.232
I mean, it's much more humane,
you know. ( laughter )

00:01:40.232 --> 00:01:42.168
And it kind of got me
thinking and...

00:01:42.168 --> 00:01:43.502
and I began to do a little

00:01:43.502 --> 00:01:45.404
background research
on elephants.

00:01:45.404 --> 00:01:48.441
<i> And in particular,
 how their minds work.</i>

00:01:48.441 --> 00:01:50.510
<i> A lot of people love
 elephants, or you know,</i>

00:01:50.510 --> 00:01:53.246
<i> collect elephants,
 but don't necessarily realize</i>

00:01:53.246 --> 00:01:56.081
<i> the cognitive abilities
 that elephants have.</i>

00:01:56.081 --> 00:01:58.951
<i> They can feel grief
 and pain and loss</i>

00:01:58.951 --> 00:02:00.820
<i> and they have
 incredible memories.</i>

00:02:00.820 --> 00:02:02.955
All of those things are
part of the elephant brain

00:02:02.955 --> 00:02:04.657
and the more I learned
about that,

00:02:04.657 --> 00:02:05.959
the more I realize this was

00:02:05.959 --> 00:02:07.693
the perfect metaphor
for the book

00:02:07.693 --> 00:02:09.128
and that I had a profession

00:02:09.128 --> 00:02:10.863
for one of the main characters
in the book.

00:02:10.863 --> 00:02:13.165
Oh. Part of the challenge
of the book

00:02:13.165 --> 00:02:15.300
is that you are writing
in different voices.

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:16.969
You are writing
in the voice of a scientist.

00:02:16.969 --> 00:02:18.972
Was it difficult as a writer

00:02:18.972 --> 00:02:22.041
to switch your brain
to do that?

00:02:22.041 --> 00:02:24.510
No, this book
is the story of...

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:25.845
this woman, Alice Metcalf,

00:02:25.845 --> 00:02:27.947
who studies elephant grief
and cognition,

00:02:27.947 --> 00:02:31.050
and she runs a sanctuary
with her husband and one night

00:02:31.050 --> 00:02:32.951
there's a horrible tragedy
at the sanctuary.

00:02:32.951 --> 00:02:35.621
And a caregiver is trampled
by an elephant.

00:02:35.621 --> 00:02:37.656
And the same night,
Alice disappears off

00:02:37.656 --> 00:02:39.325
the face of the earth.
And the only...

00:02:39.325 --> 00:02:40.960
the only person
who is a witness

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:43.195
is her three-year old
daughter, Jenna.

00:02:43.195 --> 00:02:45.865
The problem is Jenna
can remember none of it.

00:02:45.865 --> 00:02:50.236
And um... Jenna then begins
the book ten years later,

00:02:50.236 --> 00:02:51.737
believing that
her mother never

00:02:51.737 --> 00:02:53.239
would have left her willingly
and that

00:02:53.239 --> 00:02:54.874
she is going to find
this woman.

00:02:54.874 --> 00:02:56.942
And she enlists
the help of a failed

00:02:56.942 --> 00:02:58.377
psychic named Serenity,

00:02:58.377 --> 00:03:00.413
and an alcoholic detective
named Virgil.

00:03:00.413 --> 00:03:01.681
And the three of them are

00:03:01.681 --> 00:03:03.382
somehow going to find
her mother.

00:03:03.382 --> 00:03:04.951
But you also get to hear
from Alice,

00:03:04.951 --> 00:03:06.385
and the way you get to hear
from her

00:03:06.385 --> 00:03:08.087
is the way Jenna
gets to hear from her.

00:03:08.087 --> 00:03:12.058
By pouring over her research
entries and her journals,

00:03:12.058 --> 00:03:14.961
and that's what Jenna's
done for the past 10 years,

00:03:14.961 --> 00:03:16.295
is try to find her mother

00:03:16.295 --> 00:03:17.930
literally between the lines

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:19.265
of what she's left behind.

00:03:19.265 --> 00:03:21.234
Right. One of the things
that impressed me

00:03:21.234 --> 00:03:24.370
so much about the book
was the beautiful, detailed

00:03:24.370 --> 00:03:28.073
descriptions of elephant
behavior and just elephants.

00:03:28.073 --> 00:03:30.676
And so you must have done a lot
of research for that,

00:03:30.676 --> 00:03:32.044
and I'm wondering how
you went about doing

00:03:32.044 --> 00:03:33.212
- that research.
- Yeah.

00:03:33.212 --> 00:03:36.181
For this book, I knew that
I needed to see both elephants

00:03:36.181 --> 00:03:38.384
in captivity and
elephants in the wild.

00:03:38.384 --> 00:03:40.386
Because the main character
in the book

00:03:40.386 --> 00:03:42.221
whose name is Alice Metcalf,

00:03:42.221 --> 00:03:44.056
who is actually missing
for most of the book.

00:03:44.056 --> 00:03:45.958
She drives the book
as her daughter Jenna

00:03:45.958 --> 00:03:47.126
tries to find her.

00:03:47.126 --> 00:03:48.694
Alice is an elephant
researcher

00:03:48.694 --> 00:03:51.163
who studies grief and
cognition in elephants.

00:03:51.163 --> 00:03:54.500
And she studies them
in the wild in Botswana

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:57.070
and then she runs sanctuary
with her husband

00:03:57.070 --> 00:03:58.538
in New England.

00:03:58.538 --> 00:04:01.774
So, I began by doing research
at a place called

00:04:01.774 --> 00:04:04.443
The Elephant Sanctuary, which
is in Hohenwald, Tennessee.

00:04:04.443 --> 00:04:06.512
The elephants
who come to live there

00:04:06.512 --> 00:04:08.881
are elephants
who have been in circuses

00:04:08.881 --> 00:04:10.249
and zoos their entire life.

00:04:10.249 --> 00:04:12.051
And in many cases
have been very

00:04:12.051 --> 00:04:13.485
horribly abused.

00:04:13.485 --> 00:04:15.588
Coming to the sanctuary
means that they have

00:04:15.588 --> 00:04:18.624
hit the jackpot
of retirement homes.

00:04:18.624 --> 00:04:20.759
So, I got to see
how a sanctuary runs,

00:04:20.759 --> 00:04:22.494
which was really important
for the book,

00:04:22.528 --> 00:04:25.832
because a lot of the action
takes place in the sanctuary.

00:04:25.832 --> 00:04:27.200
But I also needed to know

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:29.068
what Alice's research
was about.

00:04:29.068 --> 00:04:31.136
<i> And so I went to Botswana</i>

00:04:31.136 --> 00:04:33.139
<i> and I worked with
 an elephant researcher</i>

00:04:33.139 --> 00:04:36.075
<i> who studies the migration of
 elephants in the Tuli Block.</i>

00:04:36.075 --> 00:04:37.410
And, you know,
I got to observe some

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:39.412
incredible behaviors
of elephants

00:04:39.412 --> 00:04:42.081
in their natural habitat,
which were phenomenal.

00:04:42.081 --> 00:04:44.317
Everything that you read
in the book is something that

00:04:44.317 --> 00:04:45.751
either I experienced

00:04:45.751 --> 00:04:48.053
or that I was told by someone
at the sanctuary

00:04:48.053 --> 00:04:49.154
or by this researcher,

00:04:49.221 --> 00:04:50.989
so every story in there
is true.

00:04:50.989 --> 00:04:54.159
Wow. How long were you
at each place?

00:04:54.159 --> 00:04:57.129
I was in... at the elephant
sanctuary for just

00:04:57.129 --> 00:04:59.832
a smattering of days.
It was couple of days,

00:04:59.832 --> 00:05:02.034
but it's, you know,
it's 2700 acres,

00:05:02.034 --> 00:05:04.536
most of which I wouldn't be
able to access by foot,

00:05:04.536 --> 00:05:05.704
because I'm not an elephant.

00:05:05.704 --> 00:05:07.206
( laughter )
And something that

00:05:07.206 --> 00:05:09.041
a lot of people don't realize
is that elephants

00:05:09.041 --> 00:05:11.410
in captivity often die of
foot problems,

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:13.745
<i> because they've been standing
 on concrete for so long</i>

00:05:13.745 --> 00:05:15.281
<i> and if you think about it
 in the wild</i>

00:05:15.281 --> 00:05:17.817
<i> an elephant gets to walk
 on top of different terrain.</i>

00:05:17.817 --> 00:05:20.987
So, for example, there was
an elephant at the sanctuary

00:05:20.987 --> 00:05:24.757
that had such severe cracks
in her feet, that Teva...

00:05:24.757 --> 00:05:26.759
you know the Teva company
that makes sandals?

00:05:26.759 --> 00:05:29.829
They made these giant Tevas
for her

00:05:29.829 --> 00:05:31.797
and she wore these
giant Tevas...

00:05:31.797 --> 00:05:33.933
- Wow.
- around for a while. Yeah.

00:05:33.933 --> 00:05:36.335
And then when I was in Botswana,
I was there for about a week.

00:05:36.335 --> 00:05:38.504
It was fantastic because
you get up every morning

00:05:38.504 --> 00:05:40.239
and you would
basically go on safari.

00:05:40.239 --> 00:05:42.908
And I got to see this
fantastic matriarch.

00:05:42.941 --> 00:05:45.511
The matriarch is the female

00:05:45.511 --> 00:05:47.379
head of the herd,
who runs the herd.

00:05:47.379 --> 00:05:49.181
She is usually
the biggest elephant,

00:05:49.181 --> 00:05:52.051
and the one who has
the most collective knowledge,

00:05:52.051 --> 00:05:53.652
often the oldest elephant.

00:05:53.652 --> 00:05:56.955
And she was leading her herd
up this little incline

00:05:56.955 --> 00:05:58.624
and sliding down on her butt,

00:05:58.624 --> 00:06:00.959
over and over, like it was
a little playground slide,

00:06:00.959 --> 00:06:02.361
and it was so much fun
to watch this

00:06:02.361 --> 00:06:04.363
whole herd just keep doing it.
( laughter )

00:06:04.363 --> 00:06:07.699
And then we came across
two young males,

00:06:07.699 --> 00:06:10.870
they had this giant dung ball
which was kind of gross,

00:06:10.870 --> 00:06:14.039
but they were kicking it back
and forth like it was soccer,

00:06:14.039 --> 00:06:15.942
just back and forth,
it was totally play,

00:06:15.942 --> 00:06:17.376
there was no other reason
for it.

00:06:17.376 --> 00:06:18.878
You know, so it was really fun

00:06:18.878 --> 00:06:20.546
to be able to see
behaviors like that.

00:06:20.546 --> 00:06:22.114
- That's really, really great.
- Yeah.

00:06:22.114 --> 00:06:24.584
Actually, so one of the
behaviors that fascinated me

00:06:24.584 --> 00:06:26.052
because it is
so interesting is,

00:06:26.052 --> 00:06:27.320
elephants grieving.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:30.156
There is a lot of
elephant grieving in the book,

00:06:30.156 --> 00:06:34.493
because Alice Metcalf
who is this missing mom...

00:06:34.493 --> 00:06:35.862
that her daughter, Jenna is

00:06:35.862 --> 00:06:37.930
trying find
throughout the book,

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:39.531
she studied elephant grief

00:06:39.531 --> 00:06:42.735
and that was what really
amazed me the most

00:06:42.735 --> 00:06:44.369
and people say,
"What's the coolest thing

00:06:44.369 --> 00:06:46.239
you learnt about elephants?"
And it's that

00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:49.208
they do have this depth of
understanding for loss

00:06:49.208 --> 00:06:50.876
that I would not
have been able

00:06:50.876 --> 00:06:53.445
prior to this, to attribute
to an animal.

00:06:53.445 --> 00:06:56.081
Elephants that come across
the bones of another elephant

00:06:56.081 --> 00:06:59.117
will get very somber,
their ears droop,

00:06:59.117 --> 00:07:02.621
their tails droop, they have a
complete behavioral change.

00:07:02.621 --> 00:07:04.957
And what's really interesting
is that

00:07:04.957 --> 00:07:07.160
they don't act this way around
any other bones,

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:08.961
it's just the bones of
elephants.

00:07:08.961 --> 00:07:12.765
They have been known and
very often return to the site

00:07:12.765 --> 00:07:15.368
where an elephant has died
for years afterward,

00:07:15.368 --> 00:07:17.303
as if they are paying
respects,

00:07:17.303 --> 00:07:18.737
like they are going
to the grave site.

00:07:18.737 --> 00:07:20.506
And again,
when they get there,

00:07:20.506 --> 00:07:23.409
they get very quiet,
somber, reverential,

00:07:23.409 --> 00:07:26.345
they stay for a few hours,
and then they move on.

00:07:26.345 --> 00:07:28.547
They've been known to break
into research facilities

00:07:28.547 --> 00:07:30.316
in the middle of the night,
and steal a bone

00:07:30.316 --> 00:07:31.783
that a researcher is
working with,

00:07:31.783 --> 00:07:33.218
and bring it back to the site
of that

00:07:33.218 --> 00:07:34.753
- elephant's death.
- Wow.

00:07:34.753 --> 00:07:37.456
And at The Elephant
Sanctuary in Tennessee,

00:07:37.456 --> 00:07:39.926
there's this great story about
an elephant named Sissy.

00:07:39.926 --> 00:07:43.495
Sissy survived the 1981 floods
in Gainesville...

00:07:43.495 --> 00:07:46.098
by basically being submerged
for 24 hours

00:07:46.098 --> 00:07:48.500
with just her trunk up,
like a little periscope.

00:07:48.500 --> 00:07:49.669
- Wow.
- So, she was really

00:07:49.669 --> 00:07:52.004
traumatized by the time
she came to the sanctuary

00:07:52.004 --> 00:07:55.074
and it took her very long time
to bond with other elephants,

00:07:55.074 --> 00:07:57.076
which they let happen
naturally,

00:07:57.076 --> 00:07:59.412
which of course is one of the
issues with the zoos

00:07:59.412 --> 00:08:00.746
because you know,
you can't just

00:08:00.746 --> 00:08:03.215
stick to elephants together
and expect them to be friends.

00:08:03.215 --> 00:08:05.951
So, she instead of bonding
with an elephant

00:08:05.951 --> 00:08:09.088
began to carry around a tire,
like everywhere she went.

00:08:09.088 --> 00:08:10.289
It was like
a security blanket,

00:08:10.289 --> 00:08:11.890
like a little pacifier.
And for years,

00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:14.793
she carried this tire around,
and then finally she bonded

00:08:14.793 --> 00:08:16.495
with an elephant named Tina.

00:08:16.495 --> 00:08:18.097
For years,
they were inseparable,

00:08:18.097 --> 00:08:21.133
and then one day Tina got ill,
and she died.

00:08:21.133 --> 00:08:23.301
When she died,
Sissy stayed with her

00:08:23.301 --> 00:08:24.870
the whole time she was dying,

00:08:24.870 --> 00:08:27.339
stayed by her grave
for a day after she died,

00:08:27.339 --> 00:08:29.175
and then very carefully,

00:08:29.175 --> 00:08:30.943
they watched her
take that tire,

00:08:30.943 --> 00:08:34.346
and lay it on the grave,
kinda like we place a wreath.

00:08:34.346 --> 00:08:36.549
And she left it there
for her friend.

00:08:36.549 --> 00:08:39.117
As if she knew that
her friend needed it more now.

00:08:39.117 --> 00:08:40.786
- Wow.
- Right? I know.

00:08:40.786 --> 00:08:42.721
( laughter )
Amazing.

00:08:42.721 --> 00:08:44.089
- That's really amazing.
- Yeah.

